Atomic force microscopy (AFM) and kelvin probe force microscopy (KPFM) were adopted to characterize the surface property of Au/n-Si surface and confirm the work function shift under dark and illuminated conditions. The roughness of Au/n-Si surface was obtained by a Pt/Ir tip in the contact mode of AFM, the results are shown in Supplementary Fig. 3 and related discussion is presented in Supplementary Note 3. Then the KPFM scan was performed under two distinct conditions-light on and light off which signifies the solar illuminated and dark conditions. As shown in Fig. 2a, a higher surface potential was observed under illumination. The work function of surface (φsurface) before and after illumination can be calculated as:1φsurface=φtip−CPD×e−\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
